
<section><title> Exercises </title>

	<exercises><title> Concept Review </title>

		<exercise label="c2-concept-review-01">

			<introduction>
				<p>
					Complete the following questions to test your conceptual understanding of the separation of variables method.
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<task label="c2-cr-tf-01">
				<statement correct="yes">
					<p>
						The differential equation, below, is <xref ref="separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{\cos x}{y}
						</me>
					</p>
				</statement>

				<feedback>
					<p>
						The equation is separable because it is first-order and can be written in the separable form
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = \cos x \left(\frac{1}{y}\right)
						</me>.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</task>
			
			<task label="c2-cr-tf-02">
				<statement correct="yes">
					<p>
						The differential equation, below, is <xref ref="separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2
						</me>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						The equation is separable because it is first-order and can be written in the separable form
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2 = (1)(y^2) = \underset{f(x)}{\left(\boxed{1}\right)}\underset{g(y)}{\left(\boxed{y^2}\right)}
						</me>.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</task>
				
			<task label="c2-cr-tf-03">
				<statement correct="yes">
					<p>
						The differential equation, below, is <xref ref="separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = x - 1
						</me>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						The equation is separable because it is first-order and can be written in the separable form
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = x - 1 = (x - 1)(1) = \underset{f(x)}{\left(\boxed{x - 1}\right)}\underset{g(y)}{\left(\boxed{1}\right)}.
						</me>
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</task>

			<task label="c2-cr-tf-04">
				<statement correct="yes">
					<p>
						The differential equation, below, is <xref ref="separable" text="custom">separable</xref>.
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = 15
						</me>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						The equation is separable because it is first-order and can be written in the separable form
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} = 15 = (15)(1) = \underset{f(x)}{\left(\boxed{15}\right)}\underset{g(y)}{\left(\boxed{1}\right)}.
						</me>
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</task>

			<task label="c2-cr-tf-05">
				<statement correct="no">
					<p>
						The differential equation,
						<me>
							x + \frac{dy}{dx} = y
						</me>,
						can be solved using the separation of variables method.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						The differential equation is first order, but it is equivalent to
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx}=y-x
						</me>,
						which can not be written in the form <m>\ds\frac{dy}{dx}=f(x)g(y)</m>.
					</p>
				</feedback>
				<hint>
					<p>
						Check to see that the differential equation is first order and separable.
					</p>
				</hint>
			</task>

			<task label="c2-cr-tf-06">
				<statement correct="no">
					<p>
						The differential equation,
						<me>
							\frac{dz^2}{d^2t} = \cos^2(z)
						</me>,
						can be solved using the separation of variables method.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						The differential equation is not first order, so it is not separable and cannot be solved using the separation of variables method.
					</p>
				</feedback>
				<hint>
					<p>
						Check to see that the differential equation is first order and separable.
					</p>
				</hint>
			</task>

			<task label="c2-cr-mc-01">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Identify the independent variable of the differential equation
						<me>(1 - x)y'' - 4xy' + 5y = \cos x. </me>
					</p>
				</statement>
				
				<choices>

					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<m>\ x</m>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Yes! <m>x</m> is the independent variable.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<m>\ y</m>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. Review the examples.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<m>\ y'</m>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. Review the examples.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>

				</choices>

			</task>

			<task label="c2-cr-mc-02">

				<statement>
					<p>
						What is the first step to verify the differential equation below is separable?
						<me>
							\frac{dy}{dx} + \frac{x}{y^2} = 0
						</me>
					</p>
				</statement>

				<choices>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Integrating both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. Integration should come after the equation is verified to be separable.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								Check to make sure the equation is first order.
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! The first step to verify the equation is separable is to make sure it is first order.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Combine the fractions on the left-side of the equation.
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. First of all, <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> is not a fraction. Even if it was this would not be the first step to verify separability.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Isolate <m>\ds\frac{dy}{dx}</m> on one side of the equation.
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. Isolating <m>\ds\frac{dy}{dx}</m> is required to verify the equation is separable, but there is one other detail to check first.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>

			</task>

			<task  label="c2-cr-mc-03">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Which of the following is a correct separable form for the equation
						<me>
							x\frac{dy}{dx}+10x^2y=6x^2
						</me>?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\ds\frac{dy}{dx}=6x-10xy</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							This is not written in separable form.
						</p>
					</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\ds\frac{dy}{dx}=x(6-10y)</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							This is written in separable form.
						</p>
					</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\ds\frac{dy}{dx}=x(6+10y)</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							This is written in separable form, but is not equivalent to the original differential equation.
						</p>
					</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>
		
